esses the role of the Latin Church in western Europe around the year 1000, the historiography of reform, the significance of the ‘Peace of God’ as a reformist movement, the development of the papacy in the eleventh century, the changing attitudes towards simony, clerical marriage and lay investiture, reformist rhetoric aimed at the clergy, and how reformist writings sought to change the behaviour and expectations of the aristocracy. Summarising current literature while presenting a cogent and nuanced argument about the complex nature and development of reform, this book will be invaluable for an undergraduate and specialist audience alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and social problemsxCatholic ChurchxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChurch renewalzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPapacyxHistoryyTo 1309. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChristian society.  aecclesiastical reform.  aeleventh-century Europe.  amedieval society.  apapal-sponsored movement.  apeace of God movement.  areform movement.  areligious revolution.  asocial revolution.  atenth-century Europe.1 aCushing, Kathleen G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614831540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526148315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526148315/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles